title: January 28: A day of unrest
name: January 28: A day of unrest
description: A look at the anti-government protests in Egypt on Friday, January 28, 2011.

properties.name: Ramsis Square
properties.description: At Ramsis square in the heart of the city, thousands clash with police as they leave the al-Nur mosque after prayers.Police use tear gas and rubber bullets and some of the tear gas is fired inside the mosque where women are taking refuge. Hundreds later break through police cordons to head to the main downtown square, Tahrir. But they were stopped by police firing tear gas.

properties.name: Cairo
properties.description: Troops deploy on the streets of Cairo to enforce a nighttime curfew after a day of rioting and violent chaos that was a major escalation in the challenge to president Hosni Mubarak's 30-year rule.

properties.name: Al Tahrir
properties.description: Near Tahrir, hundreds of riot police move in, anticipating the arrival of large crowds. A short while later, thousands of protesters march across a bridge over the Nile and move toward the square, where police begin firing tear gas at them.

properties.name: Egyptian Museum
properties.description: Hundreds of protesters play a cat-and-mouse game with riot police in a square just behind the Egyptian Museum on Tahrir Square. Police use tear gas and the protesters respond with rocks and chants of "illegitimate, illegitimate," a reference to Mubarak's regime.

properties.name: Assiut
properties.description: In Assiut in southern Egypt, several thousand demonstrators clash with police that set upon them with batons and sticks, chasing them through side streets.

properties.name: Alexandria
properties.description: This historic Mediterranean city is the scene of some of the fiercest fighting in the country as riot police officers fire tear-gas canisters and rubber bullets and protesters hurl paving stones at them in more than two hours of pitched battle. Raw video of stone thrown in Alexandria. Watch it here

properties.name: Suez
properties.description: Some of the most serious violence is in Suez, where protesters seize weapons stored in a police station and ask the policemen inside to leave the building before they burned it down. They also set ablaze about 20 police trucks parked near is killed in the gun battle.

properties.name: Mohandiseen
properties.description: In the upscale Mohandiseen neighbourhood, at least 10,000 march toward the city centre chanting "down, down with Mubarak." The crowd later swells to about 20,000 as they make their way through residential areas.

properties.name: National Democratic Party Headquarters
properties.description: Even the ruling party headquarters in Cairo was ablaze in the outpouring of rage, bitterness and utter frustration with a regime seen as corrupt, heavy-handed and neglectful of grinding poverty that afflicts nearly half of the 80 million Egyptians. Hundreds were looting television sets and electric fans from the burning complex of buildings used by the ruling party. Video of Egypt in turmoil. Watch it here
